0.1 BLUF

  • To see the accessibility check for this webpage, please visit WAVE.
  • Use fig.cap not fig.alt chunk option and tolerate duplicate text warning as suggested in literature.
  • See alt text guidance.
  • {Brailler} can automate descriptive chart alt text for some base and ggplots.
  • Use chunk option comment="" to remove hashes preceding code output.
  • Specify lang: "en" in the YAML.

0.2 Plot Alt Text

You can also embed plots, for example:

plot(pressure)

The above uses the fig.alt option on a base R plot. This causes an issue on WAVE as the image title attribute is set to the same value as the alt text.

ggplot(data = pressure, aes(temperature, pressure)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title  = "Some placeholder title")

Again, using fig.alt option above but this time specifying a chart title using {ggplot2} syntax does not resolve the issue with title and alt attributes having the same value.

ggplot(data = pressure, aes(temperature, pressure)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title  = "Some placeholder title")

Using fig.cap instead

Using the fig.cap chunk option avoids the issue with redundant title warning that comes with fig.alt. This provides a redundant text warning which I feel is more helpful than the redundant title warning for VI learners. Note that specifying the YAML option fig_caption: false does not resolve this issue, instead raising the redundant title warning again. This means screen reader users will hear the text twice

As advised by contractor on 2021 accessibility audit: Include blank alt text followed by the alt text in HTML p tag.

ggplot(data = pressure, aes(temperature, pressure)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title  = "Some placeholder title")

Using p tags for alt text.

Joo Young Seo suggests the use of {BrailleR} (among others) for improving VI access of data & charts. Not published to CRAN at time of writing. Maintainer appears to be working on CRAN submission.

# devtools::install_github("ajrgodfrey/BrailleR")
library(BrailleR)
VI(ggplot(data = pressure, aes(temperature, pressure)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title  = "Some placeholder title"))
This chart has title 'Some placeholder title'.
It has x-axis 'temperature' with labels 0, 100, 200 and 300.
It has y-axis 'pressure' with labels 0, 200, 400, 600 and 800.
The chart is a set of 19 points.
